The <i><b>lazy </b></i>modifier takes as argument a widget and delay the load until it is visible. The renderring to be shown during the load is the specified in the first parameter. The resulting lazy widget behaves programatically in the same way.<br><br><font face="courier new"><b>lazy </b>temporalrendering &nbsp;widget<br></font><br>It can lazily load recursively. It means that if the loaded widget has a lazy statement, it will be honored as well. (see the example)<br><br>Because a widget can contain arbitrary HTML, images or javascript, <i><b>lazy </b></i>can be used to lazy load anything.<br><br>To load a image:<br><br><font face="courier new"><b>lazy </b>"loading.." $ wraw ( img ! href imageurl)<br></font><br>or<br><br><font face="courier new"><b>lazy </b>"loading..." $ img ! href imageurl ++&gt; noWidget</font><br>